---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FlavorTabs from "../../../components/FlavorTabs.astro";
import ModuleHero from "../../../components/module/ModuleHero.astro";
import ModuleFooterNav from "../../../components/module/ModuleFooterNav.astro";
import ModuleRecap from "../../../components/module/ModuleRecap.astro";
import { flavor as gcp } from "../../../data/flavors/gcp";
import { flavor as aws } from "../../../data/flavors/aws";
import { flavor as azure } from "../../../data/flavors/azure";
import { flavor as oss } from "../../../data/flavors/oss";

const moduleId = "35-retrieval";
const entries = {
  gcp: gcp[moduleId],
  aws: aws[moduleId],
  azure: azure[moduleId],
  oss: oss[moduleId],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="35 · Retrieval quality">
  <article>
    <ModuleHero moduleId={moduleId}>
      <p>
        A working RAG pipeline finds <em>similar</em> chunks the moment embeddings exist. Retrieval quality is the
        difference between "similar" and "actually relevant" — the gap that separates a demo from something a real
        user trusts.
      </p>
    </ModuleHero>

    <h2>Hybrid search: BM25 + vector</h2>
    <p>
      Vector search alone misses exact matches — a product SKU, an error code, a person's name — because embeddings
      encode meaning, not tokens. <strong>Hybrid search</strong> runs a keyword method (BM25) and vector search
      together, then combines both rankings. It's the single highest-leverage upgrade from Module 15's plain vector
      index: it fixes the class of failures where the right chunk exists but the embedding just wasn't close enough.
    </p>

    <h2>Rerankers</h2>
    <p>
      Vector and hybrid search are optimized to be fast over millions of chunks, which means they trade away
      precision. A <strong>reranker</strong> (typically a cross-encoder) re-scores a small candidate set — say the
      top 20 — by looking at the query and each candidate together, not independently. It's slower per-item but far
      more accurate, so the pattern is: cheap retrieval for recall, reranking for precision.
    </p>

    <h2>Query rewriting and HyDE</h2>
    <p>
      Users don't phrase questions the way documents phrase answers. <strong>Query rewriting</strong> expands or
      reformulates the query before retrieval (synonyms, decomposing multi-part questions).
      <strong>HyDE</strong> (Hypothetical Document Embeddings) goes further: ask the LLM to draft a hypothetical
      answer first, then embed <em>that</em> instead of the raw question — a hypothetical answer's phrasing tends to
      resemble real answers more than a question does.
    </p>

    <h2>Measuring it: recall and precision</h2>
    <p>
      You can't tell if a retrieval change helped without a labeled set: a handful of queries with the correct
      chunk(s) marked ahead of time. <strong>Recall@k</strong> asks "is the right chunk in the top k results?"
      <strong>Precision@k</strong> asks "of the top k results, how many are actually relevant?" Module 45 builds this
      into a full evaluation suite — this module is where you start collecting the labeled examples that suite will
      need.
    </p>

    <h2>Try it in your flavor</h2>
    <FlavorTabs moduleId={moduleId} entries={entries} />

    <h2>Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Shipping vector-only search and assuming it covers keyword-style queries (SKUs, codes, names) — it doesn't.</li>
      <li>Reranking the entire index instead of a small candidate set — cross-encoders don't scale to "rerank everything."</li>
      <li>Tuning retrieval by eyeballing a few queries instead of against a labeled recall/precision set — you'll optimize for the wrong thing.</li>
      <li>Adding HyDE or query rewriting as a default for every query — they add latency and cost, and plain retrieval is often good enough for simple lookups.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
  <ModuleRecap moduleId={moduleId} />
  <ModuleFooterNav moduleId={moduleId} />
</BaseLayout>
